tatus><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F036248/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>'Mirror neurons' respond both when a person performs an action and when observing another person performing the same action. Comparable systems have been documented for pain, emotions and sensations (eg touch).&amp;nbsp; This has been linked to empathy, conceptually, because it suggests that there is a common system for dealing both with our own current state and those of other people. We may, in some literal sense, share the feelings of others because of a shared neural circuitry for self and other.&amp;nbsp; For a small number of people, seeing touch does trigger conscious tactile experiences on their own body - 'mirror touch synaesthesia'.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; This appears to be linked with heightened empathy.&amp;nbsp; This ESRC-funded research project will investigate the cognitive, affective and neural mechanisms of the tactile mirror system.&amp;nbsp; The operation of this system will be explored in the normal population and those with mirror-touch synaesthesia.&amp;nbsp; The research will consider the following: how different spatial frames of reference map between self and other; how the tactile mirror system is affected by touch to different people/objects; how individual differences in this system are linked with measures of empathy; and what distinguishes conscious from unconscious ?mirrored? percepts.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>288279</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Your bod